Environmental data

Environmental data

In ecological modelling we often aim to understand the relationship between the environment and the spatial patterns of biodiversity. Raster layers can be produced with temporal data (monthly) to generate biologically meaningful climatologies describing long-term environmental conditions.

Terrestrial environmental layers : worldclim

WorldClim has climate data for minimum, mean, and maximum temperature and for precipitation, for the period 1970-2000. Downloads can be made at different spatial resolutions, from 30 seconds (~1 km2) to 10 minutes (~340 km2).

  • Valid names in worldclim are ‘tmin’, ‘tmax’, ‘prec’ and ‘bio’;
  • Valid resolutions are 0.5, 2.5, 5, and 10 (minutes of a degree);
  • In the case of res=0.5, you must also provide a lon and lat argument for a tile;
  • In all cases there are 12 (monthly) files for each variable except for ‘bio’ which contains 19 files.

Check ?getData or https://www.worldclim.org/bioclim for more information.

S5 // Environmental data in R

# get terrestrial climate from worldclim as a stack of raster layers
airTempMaxMonths <- getData("worldclim", var = "tmax", res = 10, download = T)
plot(airTempMaxMonths)

S5 // Environmental data in R

# subset a raster layer from a stack of raster layers
airTempMaxAugust <- subset(airTempMaxMonths, 8)

# worldClim data has a scale factor of 10
airTempMaxAugust <- airTempMaxAugust/10

# plot raster layer
plot(airTempMaxAugust, main = "Global maximum temperatures in August")

S5 // Environmental data in R

Marine environmental layers : Bio-ORACLE

Bio-ORACLE is a set of raster layers providing geophysical, biotic and environmental conditions for surface and benthic marine realms at 5 arcmin (c.0.088 or 9.2 km at the equator).

Check ?sdmpredictors or https://bio-oracle.org for more information.

# list all layers for the present
layerCodes <- list_layers(datasets = "Bio-ORACLE")
# list all layers for the present; use View(layerCodes)
head(layerCodes)
layer_code name

70 BO_chlomax Chlorophyll A (maximum)
71 BO_chlomean Chlorophyll A (mean)
72 BO_chlomin Chlorophyll A (minimum)
73 BO_chlorange Chlorophyll A (range)
74 BO_cloudmax Cloud fraction (maximum)

S5 // Environmental data in R

# plot ice for the present
iceThickMinPresent <- load_layers("BO2_icethickltmax_ss")
iceThickMaxRCP85 <- load_layers("BO2_RCP85_2100_icethickmax_ss")
iceConditions <- stack(iceThickMinPresent, iceThickMaxRCP85)
plot(iceConditions, axes = TRUE, main = "Sea ice thickness (m)", ylab = "Lat", xlab = "Lon")

The main objetive of this challenge is to plot the maximum sea surface temperature in Europe for the year 2100 under two contrasting scenarios of climate change (RCP26 and RCP85)

Packages, data and functions to accomplish the challenge:

European coastline extent: xmin = -15; xmax = 40; ymin = 25; ymax = 70.5
Bio-ORACLE layer: Sea water temperature (maximum)

list_layers(datasets = “Bio-ORACLE”)

View()
load_layers()
extent(object)
crop(object)
plot(object)

Challenge 5.6 [see solution of challenge 2.9]

The main objetive of this challenge is to reclassify a set of environmental rasters and plot the potential habitat of a marine forest species (Saccorhiza polyschides) in European coastlines for the present and the future (year 2100 RCP 85) using a mechanistic approach (i.e., process based model). Compare ranges between time periods. Suitable conditions set by:

Light > 5; Salinity > 10; Max Temp < 20.5; Min Temp > 5 (Lobban & Wynne, 1981; Assis et al., 2017)

Packages, data and functions to accomplish the challenge:

Bio-ORACLE layers: Sea water temperature (maximum at mean depth); Sea water temperature (minimum at mean depth); Salinity (minimum at mean depth); Light (mean at mean depth)

source(“sourceFunctions.R”)
list_layers(datasets = “Bio-ORACLE”)
list_layers_future(datasets = “Bio-ORACLE”)
load_layers()
View()
data.frame()
reclassify()
crop(object,extent(xmin,xmax,ymin,ymax))
plot(object)
